[2025-05-25T13:25:10.744Z] Full metadata: {
  "answer": "A mudarabah is valid when it involves specific types of capital like dirhams and dinars, and when profit-sharing terms are clear and not arbitrary. It becomes invalid if conditions like guaranteed profit for one party, guaranteed loss coverage by the mudarib, or joint work conditions that prevent separation of capital and labor are stipulated. Also, if the mudarib works in an invalid mudarabah and profits, the profit belongs to the capital owner, and the mudarib gets a wage equivalent to his labor. (Sections on mudarabah validity and invalidity, pages 3-10)",
  "block_id": "3|FATAWA-QAZI-KHAN-03_hocr_searchtext.txt.gz|0|1-2",
  "block_num": "0",
  "end_page": "2",
  "interpretation": "The principle emphasizes clear contractual terms and the separation of capital and labor roles to ensure fairness and prevent exploitation in profit-sharing ventures.",
  "modern_usage": "In modern finance, this principle guides structuring partnerships and investment contracts to ensure transparency, clear profit-sharing, and risk allocation, avoiding guaranteed returns or unfair guarantees that invalidate agreements.",
